  <h2>Why Energy Monitoring Matters</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Quantify self-consumption:</strong> See exactly how much solar you use vs. export. Shift loads to daylight hours for maximum savings.</li>
    <li><strong>Catch issues early:</strong> Spot inverter problems, panel shading, or degradation before they cost you money.</li>
    <li><strong>Automate intelligently:</strong> Trigger hot water heating, EV charging, or pool pumps when solar surplus is available.</li>
    <li><strong>Validate ROI:</strong> Track actual production vs. installer estimates. Hold vendors accountable.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Key Features to Consider</h2>

  <h3>CT Clamp Quality</h3>
  <p>
    Current transformers (CT clamps) are the sensors that measure electricity flow. Look for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Split-core CTs for easy installation (no wire disconnection)</li>
    <li>Accuracy rating of 1% or better</li>
    <li>Sufficient amperage rating for your main panel</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Solar-Specific Channels</h3>
  <p>
    The best monitors have dedicated solar input channels that show:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Real-time solar production</li>
    <li>Grid import vs. export</li>
    <li>Self-consumption percentage</li>
    <li>Historical trends and comparisons</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Smart Home Integration</h3>
  <p>
    For automation enthusiasts, check compatibility with:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Home Assistant:</strong> The gold standard for local smart home control</li>
    <li><strong>MQTT:</strong> Lightweight protocol for real-time data streaming</li>
    <li><strong>REST API:</strong> For custom dashboards and scripts</li>
    <li><strong>IFTTT/Zapier:</strong> Simple cloud-based automations</li>
  </ul>

